  mainEntity: [
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Which is better, NMN or NR?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'NMN (nicotinamide mononucleotide) is one step closer to NAD+ in the biosynthesis pathway and appears to raise blood NAD+ levels 30-40% faster than equivalent doses of NR (nicotinamide riboside) in human trials. However, NR has significantly more safety research and FDA GRAS status. For maximum NAD+ elevation, NMN is better; for established safety profile, NR is better. Both are effective NAD+ precursors at 250-500mg daily.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the difference between NMN and NR?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'NMN (nicotinamide mononucleotide) and NR (nicotinamide riboside) are both precursors to NAD+, a coenzyme essential for cellular energy production that declines with age. The chemical difference: NR must first be converted to NMN before becoming NAD+, while NMN is one step closer in the pathway. NR is the form most commonly marketed as Tru Niagen (Niagen is branded NR). NMN is sold by brands like Wonderfeel Youngr, PartiQlar, and several biohacker-focused companies.' } },
