    <h2 id="nad-basics">Why NAD+ Matters for Aging</h2>

    <p>NAD+ (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide) is a coenzyme present in every cell of your body. It powers ATP production, DNA repair, and the activity of sirtuin enzymes — the "longevity genes" popularized by Harvard researcher David Sinclair. Starting in your 30s, NAD+ levels decline by roughly <strong>50% every 20 years</strong>, correlating with cellular aging, metabolic dysfunction, and age-related decline. NAD+ supplementation aims to restore youthful levels.</p>

    <p>You can't take NAD+ directly as a supplement — it's too large to cross cell membranes efficiently. Instead, you take <strong>precursors</strong> that your body converts to NAD+. The two most popular oral precursors are <strong>NMN</strong> (nicotinamide mononucleotide) and <strong>NR</strong> (nicotinamide riboside). Both work, but they differ in key ways.</p>

