    <h2 id="science">The Science: What Human Trials Show</h2>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2023 trial published in <em>Cell Reports Medicine</em> compared 300mg NMN and 300mg NR over 6 weeks. Both raised blood NAD+ significantly above placebo, but <strong>NMN raised NAD+ levels 38% more than NR</strong> at week 2. By week 6, both groups had similar NAD+ elevation, suggesting NMN reaches peak effect faster but NR catches up over time.</p>
      <cite>Cell Reports Medicine, 2023 — NMN vs NR head-to-head</cite>
    </div>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card"><strong>NMN wins on speed</strong><p>One fewer enzymatic step means faster conversion to NAD+. Noticeable effects in days vs weeks.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>NR wins on pedigree</strong><p>Discovered by Charles Brenner, studied since 2004, branded as Niagen with 10+ years of human trials.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Both raise NAD+</strong><p>Meta-analyses show 50-100% increase in blood NAD+ levels after 4-8 weeks of supplementation.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Long-term safety</strong><p>NR has 12-month trials with no serious adverse events. NMN has 6-month trials with similar safety.</p></div>
    </div>

